    "last_activity_date" : 1450269301,
    "last_edit_date" : 1450269301,
    "creation_date" : 1449751010,
    "answer_id" : 34202075,
    "question_id" : 14319732,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is a really nice Java 8 way to do it:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; list2 = list1.stream().collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Of course the advantage here is that you can filter and skip to only copy of part of the list.</p>\n\n<p>e.g.</p>\n\n<pre><code>//don't copy the first element \nList&lt;String&gt; list2 = list1.stream().skip(1).collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 1352612,
        "reputation" : 4558,
        "user_id" : 1357094,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "accept_rate" : 85,
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/73b4bd192fc3756a1ad0de1bb534f11c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
        "display_name" : "cellepo",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1357094/cellepo"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 4,
      "creation_date" : 1534047290,
      "post_id" : 36400134,
      "comment_id" : 90566876,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "This is one of the few true Answers here, as it specifies #addAll makes a shallow copy, as well as how to deep copy.  More details:  <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/715650/how-to-clone-arraylist-and-also-clone-its-contents\" title=\"how to clone arraylist and also clone its contents\">stackoverflow.com/questions/715650/&hellip;</a>"
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6818997,
      "reputation" : 3809,
      "user_id" : 5246706,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 80,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/XBcKe.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Divyesh Kanzariya",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/5246706/divyesh-kanzariya"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 28,
    "last_activity_date" : 1653381875,
    "last_edit_date" : 1653381875,
    "creation_date" : 1459765591,
    "answer_id" : 36400134,
    "question_id" : 14319732,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<pre><code>originalArrayList.addAll(copyArrayofList);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Please keep on mind whenever using the <strong>addAll()</strong> method for copy, the contents of both the array lists (originalArrayList and copyArrayofList) references to the same objects will be added to the list so if you modify any one of them then copyArrayofList also will also reflect the same change.</p>\n<p>If you don't want side effect then you need to copy each of element from the originalArrayList to the copyArrayofList, like using a for or while loop. for deep copy you can use below code snippet.</p>\n<p>but one more thing you need to do, implement the <code>Cloneable</code> interface and override the <code>clone()</code> method for SomeBean class.</p>\n<pre><code>public static List&lt;SomeBean&gt; cloneList(List&lt;SomeBean&gt; originalArrayList) {\n    List&lt;SomeBean&gt; copyArrayofList = new ArrayList&lt;SomeBean&gt;(list.size());\n    for (SomeBean item : list) copyArrayofList.add(item.clone());\n    return copyArrayofList;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1789955,
      "reputation" : 12359,
      "user_id" : 1630604,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 76,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/SME8W.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Nicolas Henneaux",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1630604/nicolas-henneaux"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1596096340,
    "last_edit_date" : 1596096340,
    "creation_date" : 1513254760,
    "answer_id" : 47813488,
    "question_id" : 14319732,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>There is another method with Java 8 in a null-safe way.</p>\n<pre><code>List&lt;SomeBean&gt; wsListCopy = Optional.ofNullable(wsList)\n    .map(Collection::stream)\n    .orElseGet(Stream::empty)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n<p>If you want to skip one element.</p>\n<pre><code>List&lt;SomeBean&gt; wsListCopy = Optional.ofNullable(wsList)\n    .map(Collection::stream)\n    .orElseGet(Stream::empty)\n    .skip(1)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList());\n</code></pre>\n<p>With Java 9+, the stream method of Optional can be used</p>\n<pre><code>Optional.ofNullable(wsList)\n    .stream()\n    .flatMap(Collection::stream)\n    .collect(Collectors.toList())\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 18059693,
        "reputation" : 669,
        "user_id" : 13127098,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/afPf2.jpg?s=256",
        "display_name" : "Nakul Goyal",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13127098/nakul-goyal"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1706555079,
      "post_id" : 48071186,
      "comment_id" : 137337843,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "This is a shallow copy, which will work fine if you are not updating any of the elements present in the lists. If the List is of Integer or such types, then this is fine. But if it&#39;s a complex object, where the value of the object might change in future iterations then both the lists will be impacted. This depends on the use-case, it can act as a requirement or bug w.r.t. the use-case."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
