    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 16,
    "last_activity_date" : 1558034869,
    "last_edit_date" : 1558034869,
    "creation_date" : 1523813080,
    "answer_id" : 49844779,
    "question_id" : 14319732,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Starting from <strong>Java 10</strong>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;E&gt; oldList = List.of();\nList&lt;E&gt; newList = List.copyOf(oldList);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/util/List.html#copyOf(java.util.Collection)\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>List.copyOf()</code></a> returns an unmodifiable <code>List</code> containing the elements of the given <code>Collection</code>.</p>\n\n<p>The given <code>Collection</code> must not be <code>null</code>, and it must not contain any <code>null</code> elements.</p>\n\n<p>Also, if you want to create a deep copy of a <code>List</code>, you can find many good answers <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/715650/how-to-clone-arraylist-and-also-clone-its-contents\">here</a>.</p>\n"
  }, {
